title: For Sale:  Lithgow Enfield with Bayonet, Accessories & Ammo - BEAUTIFUL
postcontent:
Here's one of the last true jewels of my lifelong military collection that I'm finally going to part with as I prepare to early retire. It's a Lithgow Enfield chambered in .303 British that in absolutely beautiful condition. This rifle was imported by J. Jovino of NYC whom I'm told bought all of the remaining inventory of these rifles from the Slazenger arsenal of Australia in the late 80's or early 90's. Some of these rifles came over intact and some were assembled here by Jovino from all original parts that came from Slazenger.

In any case this rifle is as close to a perfect as new specimen as you are ever likely to find. Everything is 98%+ with only the slightest handling marks. I have shot it and it functions perfectly. It's quite accurate as well. 

Rifle comes with all the accessories pictured including bayonet, canvas carry case, sling, original cleaning kit, bolt disassembly tool, ammo, bandoleer and stripper clips. 

This is a beautiful rifle and one that will continue to grow in value. I'm asking $750 for the entire outfit with pickup in the Brandon area by a Florida resident who is at least 18 years old. Unfortunately shipping firearms has become to complicated and costly for a private collector so I will not ship this rifle.

title: For Sale:  Remington Four-Barrel Pepperbox Derringer, .32 Caliber, S/N 10679
location: San Francisco Bay Area, California, United States
postcontent:
This is an extremely rare four-shot derringer. They say it is the first repeating handgun ever invented. Also known as 'Remington's New Repeating Pistol', or 'Elliot Pocket Repeater'.

Derringer: Four barrel .32 rimfire, ring trigger. Left side: "MANUFACTURED BY E. REMINGTON & SONS ILION, N.Y." ... Right side: "ELLIOT'S PATENTS MAY 29 1850 OCT 1 1861" ... Four shot double-action derringer ... trigger cycles properly, and firing pin rotates to each of four positions properly. Barrels are 3 3/8" - barrels unlock, tip forward, tip back into position, and lock, securely. The bores are in good shape - uncleaned, but the lands and grooves are visible and relatively unworn. The grips are said to be made of rosewood. The right grip appears to have been replaced, or, perhaps sanded a little too much.

They say only a few thousand of these were ever manufactured, between 1863 and 1888. But I've only seen one other for sale - and it was inoperable.

Matching serial numbers on frame and barrel assemblies.

URLs:
http://www.nramuseum.org/guns/the-galleries/the-american-west-1850-to-1900/case-21-tin-stars-sixguns-frontier-justice/remington-elliot-derringer-32rf.aspx
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remington_Zig-Zag_Derringer
http://www.remingtonsociety.com/rsa/journals/Elliot32

One reference estimates the value of this piece as less than $800. I disagree. That valuation was made half a decade ago. The only sale I've seen matching that valuation was for a piece with an inoperable firing pin. And I don't think the evaluator gave sufficient weight to just how uncommon four-barrel derringers are.

I estimate its value as more in the neighborhood of twice that - $1600.

I would happily trade this for two stock Ruger 10/22 rifles (through an FFL), and some cash.

title: For Sale:  1881 Martini Henry VR Enfield
postcontent:
Martini Enfield 1881 Rifle in .303 Caliber 
This Martini was originally built by London Small Arms Company in 1881 as a Mark III Martini Henry in Caliber 577-450. After serving the armed forces of the British Emprire and the Crown for several years, this old veteran became obsolete in the early 1890's with the advent of the new .303 Caliber Bolt Action Lee Metford and Lee Enfield rifles. Queen Victoria must have not been able to bear the thought of throwing away thousands upon thousands of perfectly good Martini Henry's so an ingenious plan was devised to rebuild and convert these Martinis over to .303 caliber. These new .303's were sent off to the Colonies for a few more good years of loyal service to the Crown until they were retired at the turn of the 20th century.

 MARKINGS: If you know what to look for, the markings on these old Martinis tell quite a story...Ian Skennerton is probably the best source for deciphering the labyrinth of markings the British military used on their weaponry...I'm not the best interpreter but I will do my best to translate. This rifle has loads of good markings, all with a story to tell. This rifle tells me it went to Enfield in 1899 for its rebuild and conversion. The LEFT side of the receiver is marked with the Crown Cypher over V.R. (that means Queen Victoria Regina), over ENFIELD (the manufacturer), over 1899 (Its Conversion Date), over M.E. .303 (Martini Enfield Caliber .303) over A.C. II. The RIGHT side of the receiver bears the Crown Cypher, over V.R., over ENFIELD, over 1881, over a smaller Crown symbol, over I.C. 1. As typical of London Small Arms markings, the original set of right-side receiver markings are extremely light and due to the Enfield rebuild in 1899, the crown is somewhat difficult to see. 

I am no gun expert, and found someone else selling the same rifle on here with much more knowledge than myself. I copied the majority of his description of this rifle has he does a much better job identifying it than I could have.

Price is $700 OBO, I would like this gun gone, so if you are interested, make an offer. Text 727 366 234zero

 The BAXS Accuracy System:
Tradition hop up systems use two points of contact on the B* (top and bottom), that allow the airsoft guns to shoot to the left or to the right. Tannerite® is unique in that it is exceptionally stable when subjected to less severe forces such as a hammer blow or being dropped. It is more than 1,000 times safer than ordinary black powder since it is not flammable and can not be initiated by any kind of flame or electricity. It is supplied as two powders which are combined to produce the explosive. Tannerite® is a trademarked name, and binary exploding targets are a patented invention by Daniel J. Tanner/Oregon. Tannerite® detonations occur at a very high velocity, producing a large explosion and cloud of water vapor. It may be useful for persons who are firing at long ranges; in this scenario, a long-range rifle shooter places targets downrange, retreats to his firing position, and fires. The shooter does not have to walk down range to see if he has a hit, the Tannerite® brand target will detonate and serve as an indicator. Since the two components are not explosive until mixed, they can legally be purchased in the USA without a license. They can be legally used for sporting purposes in conjunction with small arms, just like black powder and other exempt sporting powder. The federal government, not the state, governs the manufacture of explosives. They specifically exempt the need for an explosives manufacturing license in five separate statutes. In the CFR (Code of Federal Regulations) Publication 5400. Q&A section, question #48 expressly addresses that a license is not needed for personal, non-commercial manufacture and use of binary explosives.
